isfactory features, and progresses to a subtle, intricate, and rewarding account of his psychology of literary creation and of the audience’s reaction to literature. This study reveals, on the one hand, Wordsworth’s familiarity with the general drift of eighteenth-century of theorizing on aesthetics, especially as it dealt with the concepts of primitivism and of the sublime; and on the other, his increasing grasp of a psychological definition of the poet’s making, and the reader’s reception of literature such as is more usually associated with Coleridge. Professor Owen’s understanding of the documents and his wide knowledge of the background of the theories emerge in this important contribution to Romantic Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCriticismzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh1 aOwen, W. J. B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757840440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487578404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487578404.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK